<HTML><BODY>
<H2>Proof that level 9 is unreachable</H2>
Assign to a peg on lattice point (<I>x,y</I>) the value
<I>V</I>(<I>x,y</I>) = &theta;<sup>min{<I>y,c</I>-|<I>x</I>|}</sup>,
<BR>
where &theta; is the positive root of &theta;<sup>2</sup>=&theta;+1
(&asymp; 1.618) and <I>c</I> is a positive integer.&nbsp;
<BR>
Initially, the sum <I>S</I>(<I>c</I>) of the value of all pegs is the
sum of <I>V</I>(<I>x,y</I>) over the lower half plane,
<BR>which is
(1+2<I>c</I>)&theta;/(&theta;-1) + 4&theta;/(&theta;-1)<sup>2</sup>.&nbsp;
This is shown as follows.
<P>
<pre><font>
<I>S</I> = &sum;<sub><I>y</I>&le;0</sub> &sum;<sub><I>x</I></sub> <I>V</I>(<I>x,y</I>)
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; = &sum;<sub><I>y</I>&le;0</sub> <font size=+2>[</font> <I>V</I>(0,<I>y</I>) + 2 &sum;<sub><I>x</I>&ge;1</sub> <I>V</I>(<I>x,y</I>) <font size=+2>]</font><sub><sub>&nbsp;</sub></sub>
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; = &sum;<sub><I>y</I>&le;0</sub> <font size=+2>[</font> &theta;<sup><I>y</I></sup> + 2 &sum;<sub>1&le;<I>x</I>&le;<I>c</I>-<I>y</I></sub> &theta;<sup><I>y</I></sup> + 2 &sum;<sub><I>x</I>&ge;<I>c</I>-<I>y</I>+1</sub> &theta;<sup><I>c</I>-<I>x</I></sup> <font size=+2>]</font><sub><sub>&nbsp;</sub></sub>
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; = &sum;<sub><I>y</I>&le;0</sub> &theta;<sup><I>y</I></sup> <font size=+2>[</font>1 + 2(<I>c</I>-<I>y</I>)<font size=+2>]</font> + 2 &sum;<sub><I>y</I>&le;0</sub> &theta;<sup><I>y</I></sup>/(&theta;-1)<sub><sub>&nbsp;</sub></sub>
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; = <font size=+2>[</font>1 + 2<I>c</I> + 2/(&theta;-1)<font size=+2>]</font>&sum;<sub><I>y</I>&le;0</sub> &theta;<sup><I>y</I></sup> - 2 &sum;<sub><I>y</I>&le;0</sub> <I>y</I>&theta;<sup><I>y</I></sup><sub><sub>&nbsp;</sub></sub>
Note that &sum;<sub><I>y</I>&le;0</sub>[-<I>y</I>&theta;<sup><I>y</I></sup>] = &sum;<sub><I>i</I>&ge;0</sub> <I>i</I>&theta;<sup>-<I>i</I></sup> =  &sum;<sub>0&le;<I>j&le;i</I></sub> &theta;<sup>-<I>i</I></sup> = &sum;<sub><I>j</I>&ge;0</sub> &sum;<sub><I>i&ge;j</I></sub> &theta;<sup>-<I>i</I></sup> = &sum;<sub><I>j</I>&ge;0</sub> &theta;<sup>-<I>j</I></sup> &theta;/(&theta;-1)<sub><sub>&nbsp;</sub></sub>
So, <I>S</I> = <font size=+2>[</font>1 + 2<I>c</I> + 2/(&theta;-1)<font size=+2>]</font> &theta;/(&theta;-1) + 2 &theta;/(&theta;-1)<sup>2</sup><sub><sub>&nbsp;</sub></sub>
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; = (1 + 2<I>c</I>)&theta;/(&theta;-1) + 4 &theta;/(&theta;-1)<sup>2</sup>
</font></pre>
<P>
The net gain to <I>S</I> when jumping with a peg of value <I>v</I> is, at most,
<I>v</I>&theta;<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;-&nbsp;<I>v</I>&theta;&nbsp;-&nbsp;<I>v</I>&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.&nbsp;
<BR>
Therefore, the total value of all pegs cannot exceed its initial value.
<P>
Consider <I>c</I> = 9.&nbsp;  <I>S</I>(9)=66.687+.&nbsp;
Since the value of a peg at (0,9) is &theta;<sup>9</sup> &gt; 76,
<BR>
it follows that we cannot get a peg to the point (0,9).&nbsp;
<BR>
If we could get a peg to any point on or above the line
<I>y</I>&nbsp;=&nbsp;9
<BR>
then we could get one to (0,9) by stopping when
some peg reaches a point (<I>x</I>,9),
<BR>
and then retracing all the jumps performed shifted left by <I>x</I>,
or shifted right by -<I>x</I> when <I>x</I> is negative.
<P>
Note that the same argument can be used to show that Conway's problem,
in which diagonal jumps are not permitted cannot admit a finite sequence
of moves leading to a peg at level 5, by using the potential function
<I>V</I>(<I>x,y</I>) = &theta;<sup><I>y</I>-|<I>x</I>|</sup>.&nbsp;
In this case, the sum of <I>V</I>(<I>x,y</I>) over the lower half plane
is <I>S</I> = (&theta;<sup>2</sup>+&theta;)/(&theta;-1)<sup>2</sup>,
and the value of a single peg at (0,5) is &theta;<sup>5</sup> which
equals <I>S</I>.&nbsp;
This allows for no other pegs to co-exist, an impossibility to achieve
within a finite number of steps.
</BODY></HTML>
